## Conversation
User invoked /fix-github-issue 5421. Issue title: "Anthropic (Bedrock): when
model outputs both tool and text, only text is captured." Reporter (ChuckJonas)
says it only happens with streaming. User instructions: don't post to GH, talk
in the terminal; use a gt stack of PRs if helpful.

## Root cause
weave/integrations/anthropic/anthropic_sdk.py: anthropic_accumulator() folds
raw streaming events (create(stream=True) and beta.messages.create) into a
Message. The old code ONLY handled text: it checked
`isinstance(value, RawContentBlockDeltaEvent) and hasattr(value.delta, "text")`
and appended/extended a TextBlock. It NEVER handled:
  - content_block_start (where tool_use blocks are announced), so the ToolUseBlock
    was never added to acc.content;
  - input_json_delta deltas (which carry the tool arguments as partial JSON).
Result: streamed tool calls silently dropped from the trace output.
(Note: non-streaming create()/parse() are unaffected — should_use_accumulator()
only returns True when inputs["stream"] is truthy, and the full Message already
contains tool_use blocks.)

## Fix
Rewrote anthropic_accumulator to mirror the SDK's own accumulate_event logic
(anthropic.lib.streaming._messages.accumulate_event), but kept it self-contained
because reusing the SDK fn would need beta/regular dispatch and the beta variant
requires request_headers/output_format we don't have.
  - content_block_start -> acc.content.append(value.content_block.model_copy(deep=True))
    (copy so we never mutate the caller's event objects; deep to be safe).
  - content_block_delta -> _accumulate_content_block_delta(): address the block by
    value.index (matches SDK). text_delta extends the text block; input_json_delta
    concatenates partial_json into a transient buffer on the block and re-parses it
    into block.input via json.loads (tolerant: returns None while still partial).
  - message_start / message_delta usage + stop_reason handling left UNCHANGED
    (Chesterton's fence: the input_tokens += message.usage.input_tokens behavior is
    load-bearing for existing token-count assertions).
isinstance checks use module-level tuple constants spanning stable + beta types
(_CONTENT_BLOCK_START_EVENTS, _TEXT_DELTAS, _TEXT_BLOCKS, _TOOL_USE_BLOCKS, ...).
Verified pyright/ty/mypy all narrow correctly on the tuple-variable isinstance.

## Why json.loads, not jiter
The SDK uses jiter.from_json(partial_mode=True). I used plain json.loads with a
try/except (returns None on incomplete). The concatenation of all input_json_delta
fragments is always valid JSON by the last delta, so the FINAL persisted output is
correct; intermediate snapshots just show {} until complete. Dependency-free,
smallest change. jiter IS available (anthropic dep) if richer intermediate parsing
is ever wanted.

## CRITICAL gotcha: accumulator must never raise
op.py (_build_iterator_from_accumulator_for_op, ~line 862) wraps the accumulator
call in `try/except StopIteration` ONLY. Any OTHER exception propagates to the
outer handler which finishes the call with the exception AND RE-RAISES into the
user's `for event in stream` loop — i.e. a buggy accumulator breaks the user's
app. Hence all the defensive guards (bounds-checked index, getattr on the
transient buffer, tolerant JSON parse, fallback TextBlock if content_block_start
was missing).

## Transient buffer doesn't leak
_TOOL_INPUT_BUF_ATTR ("_weave_tool_input_json") is set via setattr on the block.
Verified it is NOT a declared pydantic field, so model_dump()/to_dict() exclude
it. weave serializes anthropic Message/blocks via to_dict()/model_dump()
(serialize.py _encode_custom_obj / _encode_try_to_dict), confirmed it never
appears in the serialized trace.

